⊢ geography
  given seed→premise ≡ "A space station in the year 3000 — humanity's last outpost after Earth became uninhabitable. Population: ~50,000. Orbiting a gas giant in the Tau Ceti system, 12 light-years from Earth."
  given? history→backstory ≡ "The Tau Ceti Ark was launched in 2847 as Project Exodus..."
  given? culture→customs ≡ "Life on the station is governed by radical resource consciousness..."
  yield layout, sectors[], environment

  ∴ Design the physical layout of the space station described in «seed→premise».
    If «history→backstory» is available (not ⊥), consider the backstory...
    [Iteration 1 context: resolve Old Foundation as original 4 km hull,
     mark expansion-era sectors, align with Great Expansion history]

-- LLM evaluation (now aware of history and culture):

  yield layout ≡ "The Tau Ceti Ark is a rotating O'Neill cylinder, 8 km long and 2 km in diameter. The original hull (the 'First Shell,' 2847-2923) comprised the aft 4 km: Old Foundation, The Ringworks, The Spine core, and the original Aft Cap. During the Great Expansion (2923), the station was extended forward by 4 km using materials from Aurelius's moons, adding The Greenway, Midtown, and Aurelius View. The station spins at 0.5 RPM to produce 0.85g along the inner surface. The cylinder is divided into six longitudinal strips alternating between habitation and window bands. A non-rotating central spine houses the docking hub, zero-g manufacturing, and the primary fusion reactor array. Two endcaps: the Forward Cap (Aurelius View, added during expansion) houses the observation deck, Council Chamber, and the navigation bridge; the Aft Cap (original) contains propulsion remnants and deep storage vaults."

  yield sectors ≡ [
    { name: "The Greenway", purpose: "Agricultural and park strip — hydroponic farms, orchards, and the station's only open sky. Runs 4 km through the expansion section. Built 2923 to feed the growing population.", era: "expansion" },
    { name: "Midtown", purpose: "Primary residential and commercial sector. Tiered hab-blocks from cylinder floor to 200m elevation. Population density: ~15,000. Built during the Great Expansion to relieve overcrowding in Old Foundation.", era: "expansion" },
    { name: "The Spine", purpose: "Zero-g central axis spanning the full 8 km. Docking bays, cargo handling, zero-g manufacturing, and the fusion reactor array. The original Spine core (aft 4 km) was extended during expansion. Access via six radial elevators.", era: "original+expansion" },
    { name: "Old Foundation", purpose: "The original construction sector — the first 4 km of habitable hull. Now mixed industrial and low-income housing. Contains the oldest structures on the station, including the original bridge (now a museum) and the Transit Memorial. Cultural significance: this is where the founding generation lived.", era: "original" },
    { name: "The Ringworks", purpose: "Engineering and life-support sector wrapping the Aft Cap. Water recycling, atmospheric processors, waste reclamation. Original construction — the station's literal lungs since day one.", era: "original" },
    { name: "Aurelius View", purpose: "Forward observation and science sector, built during expansion. The Council Chamber occupies the panoramic viewport facing the gas giant. Also houses the navigation bridge (successor to Old Foundation's original bridge), planetary science labs, and the communication array that sent the last signal to Earth.", era: "expansion" }
  ]

  yield environment ≡ "Life support: closed-loop atmospheric recycling (N2/O2 78/21 mix), CO2 scrubbers in The Ringworks with biological backup in The Greenway. The dual-system redundancy reflects the station's two eras — Ringworks (chemical scrubbing, original) and Greenway (biological, expansion-era). Water: 95% reclamation rate via distillation cascades in The Ringworks, supplemented by ice mining from Aurelius's ring system (mining operations run from The Spine's aft docking bays). Gravity: centripetal via rotation at 0.85g on the inner surface, zero-g in The Spine. Power: twin deuterium-helium-3 fusion reactors in The Spine core (original section), backup solar collectors on the window bands (added during expansion). Emergency: each sector can seal independently via pressure doors — a life-saving measure, but one freighted with cultural baggage (see: Sealed Doors taboo, the Midway Mutiny)."

-- oracle checks (aspirational under ⊢∘ co-evolve):
--   ⊨ layout describes overall structure with dimensions → ✓
