-- LLM evaluation (now aware of geography and history, with contradiction fixes):

  yield customs ≡ "Life on the Ark is governed by radical resource consciousness. Every citizen tracks their personal resource budget — water, air processing share, caloric allocation — via wrist-mounted 'life ledgers.' Waste is socially unacceptable; repair culture dominates, rooted in the founding era when the First Shell's 12,000 colonists had only what they carried. Objects are inherited, repurposed, never discarded. Greetings include the phrase 'breathe easy' — an acknowledgment that the air processed in The Ringworks is shared by all 50,000 inhabitants. Meals are communal by default, taken in sector commons; private eating is reserved for mourning or illness. Music is the dominant art form because it requires no physical materials — the Greenway hosts weekly concerts where acoustics carry through the open agricultural strip."

  yield social-structure ≡ "Governance: the Council of Sectors — six elected representatives, one per sector (The Greenway, Midtown, The Spine, Old Foundation, The Ringworks, Aurelius View), plus a Chancellor drawn by lottery from the general population. The Chancellor casts the seventh vote and serves a one-year term, preventing dynasty formation. This structure descends directly from the post-Mutiny reforms of 2863: after the faction seizure of Old Foundation's bridge, the founders distributed power so no single sector could dominate. Below the Council: a Guild system organized by function (Engineers, Growers, Medics, Teachers, Recyclers, Navigators, Keepers). Guild membership is by aptitude and choice, not birth. Social mobility is high — Guild transfers happen every 5 years during Reallocation. Class distinctions exist informally: Spine workers (zero-g laborers) are both respected for toughness and pitied for cumulative health damage from micro-gravity exposure."

  yield traditions ≡ [
    { name: "Day of Silence", description: "Annual observance on the anniversary of The Silence (2971). All non-essential systems are dimmed. Citizens gather in sector commons to share stories of Earth passed down through generations. The communication array in Aurelius View broadcasts a final signal toward Earth — never answered, always sent. No work is performed." },
    { name: "The Breathing", description: "Monthly ceremony where atmospheric processors in The Ringworks are briefly made audible throughout the station via the public address system. Citizens pause and listen to the sound of their shared air being cleaned. A reminder of mutual dependence on the engineering that keeps them alive." },
    { name: "First Light", description: "Coming-of-age ceremony at age 16. The young person spends 24 hours alone in Aurelius View's observation deck, facing the gas giant, contemplating their place in the station's future. They return to their sector commons to announce their chosen Guild." },
    { name: "Reallocation", description: "Every 5 years, citizens may change Guilds, residences, or sector assignments. A festival atmosphere — part job fair, part community celebration, held in The Greenway. Prevents social calcification. Old Foundation residents traditionally host a 'Founding Feast' during Reallocation, serving recipes from the original colonist rations." }
  ]

  yield taboos ≡ [
    { name: "Waste Hoarding", description: "Keeping broken items without repair intent. Hoarding strains the recycling systems in The Ringworks and is considered a form of theft from the community's shared resource budget." },
    { name: "Sealed Doors", description: "Locking sector pressure doors or personal quarters against neighbors without Council authorization. In emergencies, sealed doors kill — emergency protocols require free passage between sectors. The taboo traces directly to the Midway Mutiny of 2863, when the mutineers sealed the bridge in Old Foundation and 47 people died in the 11-day standoff. The phrase 'don't seal the door' means 'don't cut yourself off from the community.'" },
    { name: "Birth Overrun", description: "Having children beyond one's allocation without Council dispensation. Population is the station's most critical resource constraint — the life support systems sized during the Great Expansion support a maximum of approximately 60,000. Unauthorized births trigger immediate resource rebalancing across the offender's entire sector." }
  ]

